{
  "doc_id": "22790",
  "text": "The determination of the true intrinsic clearance from in vitro cultures, however, may be obscured by system-dependent processes. The true intrinsic clearance is the key parameter to be determined from in vitro data and reflects the pure enzyme activity toward a substrate [CITATION_1] . Its estimation should be devoid of parameters that are characteristic of the culture system itself [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In the sandwich culture, processes such as diffusion in the collagen layers, protein binding, and partitioning to the cell membranes affect the availability of the compound for clearance. If these processes are ignored, only an \"apparent\" clearance characteristic of the in vitro system is determined. Therefore, the experimental data should be fitted to a mathematical model that describes not only biotransformation but also these systemdependent processes.",
